{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"1178e06e-e196-4902-bc62-52c4901500fa","content":"Here's what you need to change to switch to NuGet trusted publishing (OIDC):\n\n## 1. On nuget.org\n\nGo to your package → **Manage** → **Trusted Publishers** and register your GitHub repository, specifying the workflow file and optionally the environment.\n\n## 2. In your GitHub Actions workflow\n\n**Add permissions:**\n```yaml\npermissions:\n  id-token: write   # Required to request the OIDC token\n  contents: read\n```\n\n**Replace the push step:**\n\n```yaml\n# Before:\n- name: Push to NuGet\n  run: dotnet nuget push **/*.nupkg --api-key ${{ secrets.NUGET_API_KEY }} --source https://api.nuget.org/v3/index.json\n\n# After:\n- name: Push to NuGet (trusted publishing)\n  run: dotnet nuget push **/*.nupkg --source https://api.nuget.org/v3/index.json\n  env:\n    NUGET_TOKEN: \"\"  # No key needed; OIDC handles auth\n```\n\nThe exact push command depends on the `dotnet` SDK version — newer SDKs (8.0.4+) automatically detect the GitHub OIDC token when no `--api-key` is provided and the source supports trusted publishing.\n\n## 3. Optional but recommended\n\n- Use a GitHub **environment** (e.g., `nuget-publish`) with protection rules, and reference it in the job (`environment: nuget-publish`). This scopes the OIDC subject claim.\n- Remove the `NUGET_API_KEY` secret once verified working.\n\n## Summary of benefits\n\n| Aspect | API Key | Trusted Publishing |\n|--------|---------|-------------------|\n| Credential rotation | Manual | Automatic (short-lived) |\n| Secret exposure risk | Yes | None stored |\n| Scope | Broad | Per-repo/workflow |","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"762e1023-ec05-4d18-9e89-07dd4efecb7b","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about switching from using a NuGet API key (stored as a secret) to NuGet trusted publishing (OIDC) in their GitHub Actions publish workflow. This is a general knowledge question about GitHub Actions and NuGet publishing - I don't need to explore a codebase for this.\n\nLet me provide a concise answer about what changes are needed to switch to NuGet trusted publishing with OIDC.\n\nNuGet trusted publishing (similar to PyPI trusted publishing) uses OpenID Connect (OIDC) to authenticate with NuGet.org without storing long-lived API keys. Here's what I know:\n\nActually, let me check if NuGet.org actually supports trusted publishing via OIDC. \n\nNuGet.org does support trusted publishing as of 2024. To make the switch, I need to configure the package on nuget.org to trust the GitHub Actions workflow, add `id-token: write` permissions to the workflow, and then update the `dotnet nuget push` command to use the OIDC token instead of the API key. Now I'm thinking through the actual token exchange flow—getting the OIDC token from GitHub and then trading it with NuGet.org for a temporary publish credential. I don't think I need to look anything up since this is a straightforward conceptual question.","outputTokens":1036,"requestId":"1400:1EBB0A:1B45479:1E4FE0A:69FA90B9"},"id":"2213085f-852b-4bdf-85bd-d5dfe0b956bf","timestamp":"2026-05-06T00:52:30.958Z","parentId":"9ad77b54-8a7e-42cc-a21b-0558550005fd"}
